{{italic title}}
'''''{{lang|cy|Hiraeth}}''''' ({{IPA-cy|hiraɪ̯θ|pron}}<ref>[http://www.geiriadur.net/sain/hiraeth.mp3 How to pronounce ''hiraeth'']</ref>) is a [[Welsh language|Welsh]] concept of longing for home, which can be loosely translated as 'nostalgia', or, more commonly, 'homesickness'. 
Many Welsh people claim 'hiraeth' is a word which cannot be translated, meaning more than solely "missing something" or "missing home." To some, it implies the meaning of missing a time, an era, or a person. It is associated with the bittersweet memory of missing something or someone, while being grateful of that/ their existence. Similarly, the Cornish equivalent is ‘hireth’;  Welsh and Cornish share common linguistic roots.
''{{Lang|cy|Hiraeth}}'' bears considerable similarities with the [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] concept of ''{{lang|pt|[[saudade]]}}'' (a key theme in [[Fado]] music), [[Galician language|Galician]] ''{{lang|gl|morriña}}'', [[Romanian language|Romanian]] ''{{lang|ro|dor}}'', [[Scottish Gaelic|Gaelic]] ''{{lang|gd|cianalas}}'', [[Russian language|Russian]] ''{{lang|ru-Latn|toska}}'' ({{lang|ru|тоска}}), [[German language|German]] ''{{lang|de|Sehnsucht}}'' and [[Ethiopia]]n ''{{lang|am-Latn|[[tizita]]}}'' ({{lang|am|ትዝታ}}).

