{{Infobox language |name=Lendu |nativename=Balendru |states=[[Democratic Republic of Congo|Congo (DRC)]] |ethnicity=[[Balendru people|Lendu]], [[Hema people|Hema]], [[Alur people|Alur]], [[Okebu]] |speakers=760,000, including [[Ndrulo language|Ndrulo]] |date=1996 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Nilo-Saharan |fam2=[[Central Sudanic]] |fam3=Eastern |fam4=[[Lenduic languages|Lenduic]] |iso3=led |glotto=lend1245 |glottorefname=Lendu |lingua=03-BAD |dia1=Badha }}
The '''Lendu''', or ''Balendru,'' are an ethno-linguistic agriculturalist group residing in eastern [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] in the area west and northwest of [[Lake Albert (Africa)|Lake Albert]], specifically the [[Ituri Region]] of [[Orientale Province]]. Their language is one of the most populous of the [[Central Sudanic languages]]. There are three-quarters of a million Lendu speakers in the DRC. A conflict between the Lendu and [[Hema people]] was the basis of the [[Ituri conflict]].
''Ethnologue'' gives ''Bbadha'' as an alternate name of Lendu, but [[Roger Blench|Blench]] (2000) lists ''Badha'' as a distinct language. A draft listing of Nilo-Saharan languages, [http://www.rogerblench.info/Language/Nilo-Saharan/General/NS%20language%20list.pdf available from his website] and dated 2012, lists ''Lendu/Badha''.
Besides the Balendru themselves, Lendu is spoken as a native language by a portion of the Hema, [[Alur people|Alur]], and [[Okebu]].
==Phonology== Demolin (1995) posits that Lendu has [[voiceless implosive]]s, {{IPA|/ɓ̥ ɗ̥ ɠ̊/}} ({{IPA|/ƥ ƭ ƙ/}}). However, Goyvaerts (1988) had described these as [[creaky voice|creaky-voiced]] implosives {{IPA|/ɓ̰ ɗ̰ ɠ̰/}}, as in [[Hausa language|Hausa]], contrasting with a series of modally voiced implosives {{IPA|/ɓ ɗ ɠ/}} as in [[Kalabari language|Kalabari]], and Ladefoged judges that this seems to be a more accurate description.<ref>{{SOWL|87–89}}</ref>
