'''Sara Aboobacker''' (born 30 June 1936) is a [[Kannada]] writer of novels and short stories,<ref name="loc">{{cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/acq/ovop/delhi/salrp/saraaboobacker.html |title=Sara Aboobacker, 1936-|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref> also active as a translator.<ref name="th">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-kerala/a-votary-of-womens-cause/article1883142.ece |title=A votary of women’s cause|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|first=Maleeha |last=Raghaviah |date=1 August 2007|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref>
Aboobacker was born in [[Kasaragod]], Kerala, India. Her books, which relate the plight of Muslim women in Kerala and Karnataka, have earned her much fame along with multiple literary awards.<ref name="loc"/> Her novel ''Chandragiriya Theeradalli'' (1984) was translated in English as ''Breaking Ties''.<ref name="th"/>
Aboobaker has translated into Kannada books by [[T. V. Eachara Warrier]], [[Kamala Das]] and [[B. M. Suhara]].<ref name="th"/>
