{{Infobox language |name=Tosu |states=[[China]] |speakers=few to none |date=2012 |ref=<ref name="Yu" /> |familycolor=Sino-Tibetan |fam2=[[Qiangic languages|Qiangic]] |fam3=[[Ersu languages|Ersuic]] |iso3=none |iso3comment=included in {{ethnolink|ers}} |linglist=qob |lingname=(not ISO) |glotto=tosu1234 |glottorefname=Tosu }}
'''Tosu''' ({{zh|s=多续|p=Duōxù}}; autonym: ''do33 ɕu33 na31''<ref>Chirkova, Katia. 2015. [https://hal-inalco.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-01180880/document A Phonological Sketch of Duoxu].</ref>) is a moribund [[Qiangic languages|Qiangic language]] of China which shows strong affiliations to both the [[Loloish languages]] and to [[Tangut language|Tangut]], the language of the [[Western Xia]]. Yu (2012) classifies it as an Ersuic language, which belongs to the [[Qiangic languages|Qiangic branch]]. There are "almost no Tosu speakers left", or "practically" no Ersu speakers left.<ref name=Yu>Yu (2012:1–2)</ref>
About 2,000 Tosu people live in Miǎnníng county and the villages around it, as well as in six outlying townships of that county, namely Hòushān (后山), Fùxīng (复兴), Huì’ān (惠安), Hāhā (哈哈), Línlǐ (林里), and Shābā town (沙坝镇).<ref>Chirkova, Katia. 2014. [https://benjamins.com/#catalog/journals/ltba.37.1.04chi/details The Duoxu Language and the Ersu-Lizu-Duoxu relationship]. ''Linguistics of the Tibeto-Burman Area'' (37). {{doi|10.1075/ltba.37.1.04chi}}</ref> Chirkova (2014) reports that it is spoken by more than 9 individuals, all in their seventies and eighties.
