'''Vitthala-natha''' ([[IAST]]: Viṭṭhalanātha, c. 1516-1588), popularly known as '''Gusainji''', was an Indian philosopher. He was the younger son of [[Vallabhacharya]], who founded the [[Pushtimarg]] religious sect of Hinduism.

== Names ==

The name Vitthalanatha is also pronounced as Vitthalnath in modern vernaculars because of [[Schwa deletion in Indo-Aryan languages|schwa deletion]]. His other names include Vitthaleshvara (IAST: Viṭṭhaleśvara), Vitthala Dikshita, or Agnikumara.{{sfn|G. V. Devasthali|1977|p=x}} In addition, he is known by the title ''Gosvami'' (Gosain-ji or Gusain-ji).{{sfn|Roshen Dalal|2014|p=1375}}

== Early life ==

Vitthalanatha was born around 1516 (between 1515 and 1518{{sfn|Roshen Dalal|2014|p=1375}}), as the second son of the religious scholar [[Vallabha]].{{sfn|G. V. Devasthali|1977|p=x}}

His devotees consider him an incarnation of the god [[Vithoba|Vitthal]] of [[Vitthal Temple, Pandharpur|Pandharpur]].{{sfn|Roshen Dalal|2014|p=1375}} He was brought up by Vallabha till the age of 15, and after that, by Vallabha's disciple Damodara-dasa.{{sfn|G. V. Devasthali|1977|p=x}}

He was proficient in the [[Vedas]], the Brahma Sutra, and the Mimansa philosophy. He studied ''nyaya'' at [[Navadvipa]].{{sfn|Roshen Dalal|2014|p=1375}}

== Religious activities ==

After the deaths of his father Vallabhacharya (c. 1530), his elder brother Gopinatha, and Gopinatha's son Purushottama (c. 1550), Vitthalanatha emerged as the main leader of the religious sect established by his father. Initially, he faced some opposition from other leaders of the sect, including Krishnadasa, a manager of the [[Shrinathji Temple]]. Krishnadasa banned Vitthalanatha from entering the temple because of personal disputes, but later, reconciled with him. Vitthalanatha forgave him, and made him in-charge of the [[Govardhan Hill]] temple.{{sfn|Richard Keith Barz|1976|p=54}}

Vitthalanatha propagated the teachings of his father, and established a religious centre at [[Gokul]].{{sfn|Roshen Dalal|2014|p=1375}}

== Literary works ==

The texts and commentaries attributed to Vitthala include:{{sfn|Roshen Dalal|2014|p=1375}}{{sfn|B. K. Bhatt|1980|p=154}}

* ''Arya''
* ''Avatarataratamya-stotra''
* ''Bhakti-hamsa''
* ''Bhakti-hetu-nirnaya''
* ''Gita-govinda-prathamashtapadi-vivriti''
* ''Jalabheda-tika''
* ''Krishna-premamrita''
* ''Nyasa-desha-vivarana-prabodha''
* ''Premamrita-bhashya''
* ''Shringara-rasa-mandanam'' (Śr̥ṅgāra-rasa-maṇḍanam)
* ''Vidvan-Mandanam'' (Vidvan-maṇḍanam)
* ''Vidya-mandana''

